metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #621
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ​​the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: Returns #500
metadata.description:
Returns is an offline-first PWA and an interactive SVG. It combines the joy of interaction, digital color and minimalist sculpture with the potential of a long running, continuously unique visual. Based on “Shipping” from 2016, it is inspired by Anne Truitt, Ugo Rondinone, Imi Knoebel, Kelly Ellsworth and many others.

A subdivision slices the viewport influenced by width, height and depth. Corners are cut by replacing them with two new points, pulled towards each other along the edges. Shapes are “rounded" by repeating this step, keeping the new points close together. As colors change, so do the relations between shapes, even if geometry changes at a slower pace. New compositions are created on click or after a timeout. This progress over time allows for infinite iterations within the space of each token. It is the promise of a seeded starting point, plus the potential for unlimited new and unique iterations and states over time.

metadata.name: Truchet Towers #70
metadata.description:
Curved Truchet tiling is laid down on a 3D plane forming an imaginary landscape of ripples.

The longest continuous line created by the tiling is removed, cutting a path through the terrain.
This occurs within 3D space and may or may not appear within the confines of the canvas frame,
but most likely will appear.

A tower rises up to wherever a circle is created by the tiling. Driven by the random
tiling, zero or several of these may appear within the frame. Shadows differ in each mint.

In addition to working on decorative tiling, Sébastien Truchet worked on canals and sundials,
forming the inspiration for the exploration of shade and shadow in this work.

Mints will have a variety of earth-tone background colors with each perspective of the scene
slightly different to produce diverse results.

As I researched Sébastien Truchet I learned that he worked with hydraulics and canal design,
as well as sundials. This became the inspiration for my new shading and shadowing technique used
in this piece.

For me this piece evokes a sense of agriculture, and connects me to an imaginary
landscape that could have looked familiar to Truchet in 18th century France.

This work was created with my own javascript, utilizing my polyline path helper library I
maintain at https://github.com/markroland/path-helper.

metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #341
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I’m always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There’s something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #663
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Zephyr #468

metadata.name: ðolmen #129
metadata.description:
ðolmen is a generative art project by Diego Pintos.
It draws rectangles with points instead a plain color or border. With some variations in the distribution of this points, we get a kind of noise depth effect.

12 carefully selected palettes. Based in Art Masterpieces and in Nature.
· Gioconda (Leonardo da Vinci)
· Guernika (Pablo Picasso)
· Nighthawks (Edward Hopper)
· Meninas (Diego Velazquez)
· Judith beheading Holofernes (Caravaggio)
· Al Siq (nature)
· guacamayo (nature)
· Salamanca (nature)
· mostaza (nature)
· Timanfaya (nature)
· piedra (nature)
· firefall (nature)

ðolmen builds 10 compositions:
· Square
· PersonChen's Style
· Equilibrium
· Hanging
· Pyramid
· Row
· Column
· 3 columns (randomly aligned)
· 3 rows (randomly aligned)
· Frame

Density
· Tiny: Less than 35 rects. Rare
· Small: Less than 100 rects. Common.
· Medium: Less than 250 rects. Common.
· High: Less than 350 rects. Common.
· Massive: Less than 500 rects. Rare.
· Ultra: More than 500 rects. Rarest.

Rarities
· Rectangle filling type: Filled (95%) or unfilled (5%)
· Monochrome: Just black and white. Always unfilled. (1%)
· Dark mode: Dark background (20%). Dark mode can be monochrome.
· Habitable (90%). See humans later.

Humans
ðolmen can host tiny humans. Contains a little code that draws humans looking down, in order to to provide size perspective.

Minting
Each ðolmen contains all rarities inside. As a ðolmen collector, you can display your final piece in all available formats, and rarity owners can display the regular filled composition. In addition, this can help if you want to print one or more formats.

Tricks and Keys
ðolmen is responsive, you can zoom out your browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas
'd' toggle dark mode
'f' toggle fill mode
'm' toggle monochrome

More info and visual description:
https://thelirios.com/dolmen/

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: alchemy(maxima) #69
metadata.description:
This collection takes its main inspiration from the Turkish marbling art “Ebru” and tries to spin it with a golden twist, hence alchemy :) 

alchemy(maxima) tries to create a composition either using one of the two grid types, and sometimes breaking them or in a totally chaotic way, but uses color harmony and rhythm to keep the chaos in check and the resulting image still somewhat interesting and sometimes golden-ish…

The name includes “maxima” because this is the first part of a 2-part series; its companion collection “alchemy(minima)” will be released soon and as per my tradition will be freely available to maxima holders.

From the proceeds of the primary sales of alchemy(maxima),

- 33% will directly go to The Processing Foundation,
- 33% will fund the greater evil,
- 34% will be used to grow my collection.

So in a way, all the proceeds will go back into the ecosystem. This is my way of making up for taking tez out with my donations earlier.

If you are wondering what the hell “the greater evil” is, read about it here : 

https://twitter.com/evilnft/status/1544320804304961536?s=20&t=AoEfLfn32tGNR8JTi5Jjng

And find it here:

https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/the%20greater%20evil/collection

—

About the work: 

- 22 palettes - 7 new, 15 recycled,
- 3 main variants,
- 4 sub-variants each,
- 9 visible and some hidden features :)
- After going live, press “s” to save a png (at your screen resolution)
- No hi-res output due to the warp manipulating the pixel array directly, which means higher res equals to much higher computation time.

Thank you all in advance and have a good day!

Warp functions are based on this article by Inigo Quilez : https://iquilezles.org/articles/warp/

DISCLAIMER : I am not a good coder, I have tried to fix my past mistakes from my earlier projects to make some room for new mistakes :) I am learning on the way and certainly hoping that there aren't any huge bugs or anything, so you can enjoy your mint! Please hit me up if you have any concerns after minting and we can discuss a solution.

metadata.name: Dithered Gradients #360
metadata.description:
Each Dithered Gradient is generated from an algorithm derived from Pixel Blobs II. Pixels are initially placed onto a canvas in 4 orderly patterns. Every color grows in a deterministic pattern randomly generated before the canvas initializes. Interesting dither patterns are created when 2 colors collide.

Features:
- Saturation: (None=75%, +25%=18.75%, -25%=6.25%)
- Inverted Colors: (true=75%, false=25%)
- Pattern: (Horizontal=75%, Vertical=22.5%, X=1.875%, Box=.625%)

Co-released in partnership with fauxjebus May 10, 2022
